 topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Trenoweth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Cornish: locative name from one or more of at least twenty places in Cornwall named with Cornish  <i>tre</i> ‘house, settlement’ +  <i>nowyth</i> ‘new’, with the spellings  <i>Trenewth</i>,  <i>Trenouth</i>,  <i>Trenowah</i>,  <i>Trenower</i>,  <i>Trenoweth</i>,  <i>Trenowth</i>,  <i>Trenute</i>, or  <i>Trenuth</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Trenouth","meanings":["Cornish:  see  Trenoweth  ."]},{"name":"Trenwith","meanings":["Cornish:  see  Trenoweth  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret de Trenoweth was born in 1189, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 sons with Robert Carminow. She died in 1240, in her hometown, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1189–1240":"1189–1240","1185–1256":"1185–1256","1210–1287":"1210–1287","1212–Male":"1212–Surnud","1212":"1212","1256":"1256","1189":"1189","Abt 1210":"umbes 1210","1287":"1287","1210":"1210","1240":"1240","1185":"1185","about 1212":"umbes 1212","Trenowyth, Cornwall, England":"Trenouth, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1189–1240":"1189–1240","1185–1256":"1185–1256","1210–1287":"1210–1287","1212–Male":"1212–Kuollut","1212":"1212","1256":"1256","1189":"1189","Abt 1210":"noin 1210","1287":"1287","1210":"1210","1240":"1240","1185":"1185","about 1212":"noin 1212","Trenowyth, Cornwall, England":"Trenouth, Cornwa